Based on the Nodal Point philosophy ("Obsidian & Glass") and the capabilities defined in your architecture [Source 317, 1183], here is the forensic blueprint to upgrade your AI interface.
We are moving away from "chatting" and towards "data orchestration."
1. The "Markdown" Fix: Converting ** to Signal
You do not want to see asterisks. You want to see High-Fidelity Data. You must override the default Markdown rendering in your chat component.
The Directive: Do not strip the **. Use a custom renderer to transform **Text** into a High-Contrast Data Artifact.
Implementation (Tailwind/React):
// In your Markdown Renderer component
components={{
  strong: ({ node, ...props }) => (
    <span className="font-mono font-bold text-white bg-white/10 px-1 rounded-sm border border-white/5 tracking-tight shadow-[0_0_10px_-2px_rgba(255,255,255,0.2)]">
      {props.children}
    </span>
  )
}}
• Result: When the AI says "Strike Price: $0.042", the user sees a glowing, glass-encased number. It pops against the dark background [Source 881, 1182].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. The Identity Node (Clickable Contact/Account Cards)
You asked for cards instead of tables. In Nodal Point, we call these "Identity Nodes."
The Trigger: When you ask "Who is Tonie Steel?" or "Show me Camp Fire First Texas," the AI detects the intent via get_contact_details or get_account_details [Source 317].
The Output Structure (JSON): The AI must return a type: "identity_card" JSON object, not text.
The Visual (The Card):
• Container: w-full max-w-md bg-zinc-900/80 border border-white/10 backdrop-blur-xl rounded-2xl overflow-hidden hover:border-[#002FA7]/50 transition-colors cursor-pointer.
• Header:
    ◦ Left: A large "Letter Glyph" (e.g., "TS") in a glass square [Source 1185].
    ◦ Right: A "Status LED" (Active/Green or Risk/Red).
• Body:
    ◦ Name: White, sans-serif, large.
    ◦ Title/Industry: Zinc-500, mono.
• Footer (The Uplink):
    ◦ A full-width button effect: Group-hover:bg-[#002FA7]/10.
    ◦ Action: Clicking the card executes router.push('/network/people/${id}').
Why this works: It creates a tactile bridge between the "Chat" layer and the "Database" layer.

